of national sovereignty, war and technology, identity politics, the Gulf War, and the tragic plight of Sarajevo. The essay “Eulogy for the Mêlée,” in particular, is a brilliant discussion of identity and hybridism that resonates with many contemporary social concerns. As Nancy moves through the exposition of his central concern, being-with, he engages a number of other important issues, including current notions of the “other” and “self” that are relevant to psychoanalytic, political, and multicultural concepts. He also offers astonishingly original reinterpretations of major philosophical positions, such as Nietzsche’s doctrine of “eternal recurrence,” Descartes’s “cogito,” and the nature of language and meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aPhilosophy -- Poststructuralism and Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361900540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619005/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles